SIMPLE: ne
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: ne
<hw>ne</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>ne</ets>.
See <er>No</er>.]</ety> <def>Not; never.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He never yet no villany <qex>ne</qex> said.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ne</xex> was formerly used as the universal adverb
of negation, and survives in certain compounds, as <xex>n</xex>ever (=
<xex>ne</xex> ever) and <xex>n</xex>one (= <xex>ne</xex> one). Other
combinations, now obsolete, will be found in the Vocabulary, as
<xex>nad</xex>, <xex>nam</xex>, <xex>nil</xex>. See <er>Negative</er>,
2.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ne</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: ne
<hw>ne</hw>, <pos>conj.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Ne</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos>]</ety> <def>Nor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No niggard <qex>ne</qex> no fool.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ne . . . ne</b></col>, <cd>neither . . . nor.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neaf</ent>⟦br⟧
